comments[2]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-06-19T15:49:09.715Z",claude-code-agent,"Filed from a maintainer session on Linux. Root cause is Windows-only and not safely reproducible/verifiable from POSIX without risking the green 100%-coverage suite, so it needs a windows-latest runner to land + verify the fix. Non-blocking for releases: the daily Release workflow is independent of nightly and is green (npm @2026.6.19). macOS's single failure is already fixed (commit 8bc37a22)."
  "2026-06-19T19:20:05.038Z",claude-code-agent,"Partial progress (PR: auto-release-sentry-gate-window-and-alerting): fixed the two hardcoded POSIX-separator assertions called out in this issue — init-command.spec.ts pmRoot now asserts path.resolve(/repo, /repo/.agents/pm) and schema-command.spec.ts asserts path.join(.agents, pm, schema, types.json) instead of forward-slash literals. Added a win32-simulated regression guard (runtime-schema-path-win32-guard.spec.ts) that mocks node:path to path.win32 so a POSIX per-PR runner catches a schema-path separator regression rather than only the nightly. REMAINING (needs a Windows runner to verify): the file://-URL TS dynamic-import cluster (~18 specs computing pathToFileURL(src/*.ts) — chiefly cli-main-errors.spec.ts) that throws SyntaxError on Windows because Vitest does not transform absolute file:// specifiers there; that bulk and a per-PR windows-latest matrix guard stay open."
files[3]{path,scope,note}:
  tests/unit/commands/init-command.spec.ts,project,Assert pmRoot with path.resolve not a POSIX literal
  tests/unit/commands/schema-command.spec.ts,project,Assert schema types.json hint with path.join not a POSIX literal
  tests/unit/core/schema/runtime-schema-path-win32-guard.spec.ts,project,win32-simulated separator regression guard
body: "## Summary\n\nThe nightly validation matrix has been **red on `windows-latest` since 2026-06-14**, and the failure count has grown from 5 tests (run 27493008584, commit 647cb9b3) to **373 tests across 30 files** (run 27816467001, commit 87229daa, 2026-06-19). It went unnoticed until the new failure alerting (pm-ehbb / PR #300) began surfacing it. POSIX (ubuntu/macos) and the per-PR `Gates` matrix are all green, so this only reproduces on Windows in the full nightly suite.\n\n`macos-latest` had a *single* failure (`/private/var` vs `/var` TMPDIR symlink canonicalization in `extension-command.spec.ts`); that one is **already fixed** by commit `8bc37a22` (\"fix(ci): stabilize extension file-alias realpath test\"), which postdates the failing nightly — the next nightly should be green for macOS. This issue tracks the **Windows** failures only.\n\n## Primary root-cause hypothesis (the `SyntaxError` cluster — the bulk of the 373)\n\nThe dominant signature is:\n\n```\nAssertionError: expected [Function] to throw error including 'EXIT:0' but got 'Invalid or unexpected token'\nAssertionError: promise rejected \"SyntaxError: Invalid or unexpected token\" instead of resolving\n```\n\n~18 unit specs drive **TypeScript source** for coverage by computing a file URL and dynamically importing it, e.g. `tests/unit/cli/cli-main-errors.spec.ts:182`:\n\n```ts\nconst mainUrl = pathToFileURL(path.resolve(\"src/cli/main.ts\"));\nconst loaded = (await import(mainUrl.href)) as { runPmCli: (argv: string[]) => Promise<void> };\n```\n\nOn POSIX, Vitest's transform pipeline intercepts the `file://` specifier and transpiles the `.ts` on the fly. On Windows the specifier is `file:///D:/...`, which appears **not** to be intercepted, so Node executes the raw TypeScript and throws `SyntaxError: Invalid or unexpected token` at the first type annotation. Every test in those files then fails identically, which matches the fan-out across otherwise-unrelated suites (sentry, search, telemetry, governance, bundle-cli, …).\n\nCandidate fixes (need a Windows runner to verify): import the source via a relative module specifier Vitest can transform (`await import(\"../../../src/cli/main.ts\")`) instead of a computed absolute `file://` URL; or normalize the dynamic-import specifier for win32; or load via Vitest's `import.meta` / a shared helper that is platform-correct.\n\n## Secondary failures (hardcoded POSIX separators)\n\nIndependent of the SyntaxError cluster, a few assertions hardcode `/`:\n\n- `expected { pmRoot: 'D:\\repo\\.agents\\pm' } to deeply equal { pmRoot: '/repo/.agents/pm' }` — a resolve test asserts POSIX-joined paths.\n- `expected '…' to contain '.agents/pm/schema/types.json'` — error-message assertion expects forward slashes; Windows emits `.agents\\pm\\schema\\types.json`.\n\nThese should normalize separators (e.g. compare against `path.join(...)` or `.split(path.sep).join(\"/\")`) rather than literal `/`.\n\n## Affected runs / evidence\n\n- Failing run (Windows, 373/30): https://github.com/unbraind/pm-cli/actions/runs/27816467001 (job 82318768285)\n- First red (Windows, 5/5): run 27493008584 (2026-06-14, commit 647cb9b3)\n- Last green: run 27460855284 (2026-06-13, commit fb8209ff)\n- macOS single failure already fixed in `8bc37a22`.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] `windows-latest / Node 20` nightly `Test` step is green (0 failed) on the full suite.\n- [ ] The `file://`-URL TS dynamic-import pattern is replaced with a platform-correct approach across the ~18 affected specs (or a shared test helper), verified on a Windows runner.\n- [ ] The two POSIX-separator assertions are normalized.\n- [ ] No coverage regression (still 100/100/100/100 on POSIX) and no new `any`.\n- [ ] A `cross-platform` regression guard is added so a Windows-only TS-import or separator regression fails a *required* (per-PR) check, not just the nightly."
